<li id="cite_note-bukhari-39"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-bukhari_39-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFibn_Ismāʻīl_Bukhārī1981" class="citation book cs1">ibn Ismāʻīl Bukhārī, Muḥammad (1981). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=tB9quQEACAAJ"><i>Ṣaḥīḥ Al-Bukhārī: The Translation of the Meanings of Sahih Al-Bukhari</i></a>. Vol.&#160;v4. Translated by Muhsin Khan, Muhammad. Medina: Dar al-Fikr. pp.&#160;34–204.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=%E1%B9%A2a%E1%B8%A5%C4%AB%E1%B8%A5+Al-Bukh%C4%81r%C4%AB%3A+The+Translation+of+the+Meanings+of+Sahih+Al-Bukhari&amp;rft.place=Medina&amp;rft.pages=34-204&amp;rft.pub=Dar+al-Fikr&amp;rft.date=1981&amp;rft.aulast=ibn+Ism%C4%81%CA%BB%C4%ABl+Bukh%C4%81r%C4%AB&amp;rft.aufirst=Mu%E1%B8%A5ammad&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DtB9quQEACAAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJihad" class="Z3988"></span>. Quoted in <cite id="CITEREFStreusand1997" class="citation journal cs1">Streusand, Douglas E. (September 1997). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.meforum.org/357/what-does-jihad-mean">"What Does Jihad Mean?"</a>. <i>Middle East Quarterly</i>: 9–17. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20140908145532/http://www.meforum.org/357/what-does-jihad-mean">Archived</a> from the original on 8 September 2014<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">24 August</span> 2014</span>. <q>In hadith collections, jihad means armed action; for example, the 199 references to jihad in the most standard collection of hadith, Sahih al-Bukhari, all assume that jihad means warfare.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Middle+East+Quarterly&amp;rft.atitle=What+Does+